On Saturday, September 27, 2003, at 03:46  PM, Doktor Tim wrote:

> Yes, pull it and clean it of all varnish and deposits.  A ridge of 
> varnish on the butterfly or throat can play mayhem with idle air flow. 
> Blow those vacuum ports clear. Those are tiny holes at/near the edge 
> of the closed butterfly and must be clean for good clean spark 
> advance/retard action. I use NAPA Throttle Body Cleaner (very 
> effective on this type deposit) and a small brush and scribes and 
> little screwdrivers and get every bit of crud out of there. USE A FACE 
> SHIELD. You don't want even the tiniest bit of that chemical splashed 
> in your eyes or up your nose, and if you do this right, it WILL spit 
> back at you.

Would plain old carb cleaner do the trick?  My FLAPS has plenty of carb 
cleaners to choose from, but I couldn't find any specifically labeled 
for FI throttle bodies.

What's the NAPA cleaner made of?  Gumout carb cleaner seems to be 
mostly acetone and MEK.

